00:36:16.690 --> 00:36:23.609
Justin Florentine (Besu): No. No, no, I just wanted to present… I just wanted to present it as a broader discussion.

336
00:36:23.610 --> 00:36:23.980
Gottfried Herold: Yeah.

337
00:36:23.980 --> 00:36:40.240
Justin Florentine (Besu): Because there is optionality in Lucid, and I don't know that we're… and I think probabilistic farming is a good example of it, but anytime you can withhold a key, you're going to have that optionality, so… Yeah. Is this a deal-breaker, right?

338
00:36:40.880 --> 00:36:49.140
Gottfried Herold: I mean, this is the basic question that, in the end of the day, ACD has to answer, whether Lucid gets CFI or not. Because this is really the…

339
00:36:50.820 --> 00:36:59.009
Gottfried Herold: the issue with Lucid, and that's something we cannot solve. I mean, the main sort of starting point for Lucid, or sort of the design rationale for Lucid is

340
00:36:59.010 --> 00:37:16.789
Gottfried Herold: I mean, we do not have threshold encryption, that is good enough, so, we will always have some kind of optionality without these cryptographic tools. Those it is kind of the best we can do, but it has this optionality issue. Whether, sort of, this is a deal-breaker, then, well, then, well, then there we are, and we won't have anything.

341
00:37:16.790 --> 00:37:19.589
Gottfried Herold: That's basically just the reality of the situation.

342
00:37:19.740 --> 00:37:24.940
Justin Florentine (Besu): Okay, so I can actually take that to ACD, and we can get some clarity on that.

343
00:37:24.940 --> 00:37:28.379
Gottfried Herold: Yeah. So, this is… at the end of the day, this is really…

344
00:37:28.900 --> 00:37:32.269
Gottfried Herold: The main… that's the main issue, and it's always been kind of…

345
00:37:32.970 --> 00:37:43.210
Gottfried Herold: there, and kind of open and everything. It's not… it's just that it's something where… just something… it's just a downside of Lucy that we have to accept if we want anything.

346
00:37:43.510 --> 00:37:44.310
Justin Florentine (Besu): Okay.

347
00:37:44.900 --> 00:37:45.570
Justin Florentine (Besu): Cool.

348
00:37:46.770 --> 00:37:51.139
Justin Florentine (Besu): We'll talk to people about that, and we'll see, we'll see what the vibes are.

349
00:37:51.490 --> 00:37:52.060
Gottfried Herold: No.

350
00:37:52.480 --> 00:38:10.019
Gottfried Herold: The more interesting kind of aspects of the… where we could potentially do something are actually the other option… the other optionality things. I mean, this kind of classification of optionality into probabilistic frontrunning, I mean, this probabilistic frontrunning is just a way to exploit optionality.

351
00:38:10.020 --> 00:38:22.229
Gottfried Herold: On the design side, there is, like, the other sort of optionality things, which is called builder optionality, which is a bit more interesting, interesting, not in the sense that it's as bad as the reveal optionality, where the

352
00:38:22.510 --> 00:38:28.250
Gottfried Herold: Key Provider basically fails to reveal, but this kind of builder optionality, which is something that at least

353
00:38:28.600 --> 00:38:32.100
Gottfried Herold: may be amenable, or where the design

354
00:38:32.440 --> 00:38:40.480
Gottfried Herold: may actually be able to do something about it, which is essentially related to these PTC tie-style votes.

355
00:38:41.520 --> 00:38:45.130
Gottfried Herold: I mean, bear…

356
00:38:45.770 --> 00:39:05.339
Gottfried Herold: in some sense, I mean, the problem is, to some extent, that we are using, just to explain to those who did not read this, I mean, we are basically using a FOCIL-style mechanism to force inclusion, so basically, once you reveal your keys, we…

357
00:39:05.460 --> 00:39:09.729
Gottfried Herold: force inclusion into the next block. We have to do that because the…

358
00:39:09.840 --> 00:39:23.579
Gottfried Herold: the transactions are not decryptable by anyone, so we have to actually now execute them. Yes. Obviously. And in some sense, this, we use Fossil, and Fossil is a mechanism that basically ensures that if the

359
00:39:23.770 --> 00:39:37.089
Gottfried Herold: On a ski provider basically makes it widely available, then the PTC votes will all say, hey, this was available, and so we can reasonably force the next included to sort of include it, provided everything works out, that things decrypt correctly, and whatnot.

360
00:39:37.220 --> 00:39:47.060
Gottfried Herold: Now, the problem is that, the FOCIL as a mechanism itself only makes sure that if you provide everything, then

361
00:39:47.060 --> 00:40:04.949
Gottfried Herold: you also get included. It does not say anything about the converse. And the converse in this case would be, if you do not make everything available, you do not include it. But observe that, for Lucid, which, for Fossil, which is purely a censorship resistance mechanism, this doesn't matter.

362
00:40:05.180 --> 00:40:13.639
Gottfried Herold: However, for Lucid, this means the following. Let's say you have some key that you never release, except to the builder.

363
00:40:14.300 --> 00:40:28.809
Gottfried Herold: then the builder could, if you do not have any kind of thing for the converse, could just say, hey, look at what the other keys are released, and depending on that, yeah, I have seen it, so I can just include it. So you have to basically constrain the builder in some way.

364
00:40:29.060 --> 00:40:33.909
Gottfried Herold: To make sure that, sort of, whether you must not

365
00:40:34.090 --> 00:40:44.370
Gottfried Herold: release keys that you have… must not include transactions for which you… for which the keys were not, sort of, made widely available. The problem is that you…

366
00:40:44.370 --> 00:40:55.490
Gottfried Herold: Basically, would need to have, in order to make this kind of, in a really secure and safe way, which leaves the builder no free choice, essentially would need to run some kind of consensus protocol on

367
00:40:55.900 --> 00:41:10.579
Gottfried Herold: which keys were released and which were not. Either you add another extra round, or you basically, accept the fact that there will be some wiggle room. So basically, if some keys are sort of made

368
00:41:10.790 --> 00:41:17.119
Gottfried Herold: sort of only somewhat available, then the builder has a choice. And this, in fact, yeah, this gives you…

369
00:41:17.560 --> 00:41:19.280
Gottfried Herold: Some choice for the builder.

370
00:41:19.470 --> 00:41:27.800
Gottfried Herold: And this choice for the builder is another form of optionality, which has other applications that you can sort of use them. They are probably not as bad.

371
00:41:28.770 --> 00:41:30.349
Gottfried Herold: But they are still there.

372
00:41:30.700 --> 00:41:45.520
Gottfried Herold: And there are ways to sort of mitigate this problem, at least, which would be, to, in particular for the PTC, case, would be to actually punish, equivocations of the PTC vote.

373
00:41:45.730 --> 00:41:50.449
Gottfried Herold: Well, maybe vocations in the PTC boat, sort of excavate the problem.

374
00:41:50.660 --> 00:41:51.310
Gottfried Herold: Or…

375
00:41:51.310 --> 00:41:57.850
Justin Florentine (Besu): And this punishment would be because they exploited that, equivocation leniency, is what you're saying, right?

376
00:41:57.850 --> 00:42:22.459
Gottfried Herold: Yeah, I mean, this is one… I mean, you do not really need the vocations, but if revocations make it easier. Because what you can do is, in some sense, what the current Lucid proposal basically says is that if more than 50% of the PTC voted for it, then you must include, and if less than 50%, if more than 50% voted that they did not see it, you must not see it, roughly speaking.

377
00:42:22.540 --> 00:42:40.280
Gottfried Herold: The problem is there's some leeway, there's two sources of leeway. One leeway is that, there is sort of a distinction between they've seen it early and they've seen it late, which is sort of enough to actually already give you some builder optionality, and the other leeway comes from

378
00:42:40.350 --> 00:42:46.179
Gottfried Herold: PTC members who actually advocate, so they vote for both, they have seen it and they have not seen it.

379
00:42:46.210 --> 00:43:03.209
Gottfried Herold: And those evocation votes basically count towards both options, and there's no punishment for it. And this makes better optionality easier to exploit and worse, and we could… we could simply at least disincentivize it easily by adding some kind of penalty for evocations.

380
00:43:05.180 --> 00:43:06.030
Justin Florentine (Besu): Okay.

381
00:43:06.610 --> 00:43:14.419
Gottfried Herold: So, this is a bit more interesting than the other optionality, not because it's worse, but it's because there is actually some things we can do about it.

382
00:43:14.420 --> 00:43:15.040
Justin Florentine (Besu): Nope.

383
00:43:15.250 --> 00:43:16.530
Gottfried Herold: On the design side.

384
00:43:17.740 --> 00:43:19.590
Justin Florentine (Besu): I'm gonna talk to Potuz about this.

385
00:43:21.250 --> 00:43:25.899
Justin Florentine (Besu): But I'm gonna talk to POTUS about this, get his thoughts on it, since he's needy in Wonderland.

386
00:43:25.900 --> 00:43:29.429
Gottfried Herold: Yeah. I mean, the fundamental problem really is that, I mean.

387
00:43:29.680 --> 00:43:38.519
Gottfried Herold: It's not… it's not 100% solvable, just to be clear, because of lateness of votes, and because there's inherently some kind of,

388
00:43:38.720 --> 00:43:43.799
Gottfried Herold: mini consensus protocol, but, I mean, you can sort of make it less exploitable.

389
00:43:47.510 --> 00:43:48.690
Justin Florentine (Besu): Cool.

390
00:43:52.210 --> 00:43:52.900
Justin Florentine (Besu): Okay.

391
00:43:55.790 --> 00:43:59.349
Justin Florentine (Besu): Anybody else want to chime in on that one? It's an interesting one.

392
00:44:05.440 --> 00:44:06.390
Justin Florentine (Besu): Okay.

393
00:44:10.810 --> 00:44:18.540
Justin Florentine (Besu): Alright, we're getting, we're getting down to the end here, we only got 9 minutes left on time, so…

394
00:44:19.770 --> 00:44:25.010
Justin Florentine (Besu): One of the things that was an interesting point here was over-agnosticism of the lucid design, meaning that

395
00:44:25.440 --> 00:44:43.600
Justin Florentine (Besu): We don't… we do spec out, like, okay, here's a, you know, symmetric means of doing stuff with the Cha-Cha Poly stuff, but we don't necessarily commit to it, and we try to keep it kind of agnostic as far as, like, how the cryptography ever, how the cryptography works.

396
00:44:45.360 --> 00:44:48.470
Justin Florentine (Besu): One of the things that I was thinking was that

397
00:44:48.770 --> 00:44:53.480
Justin Florentine (Besu): We keep the agnosticism, but we, constrain it.

398
00:44:54.150 --> 00:44:58.800
Justin Florentine (Besu): Meaning that… Yes, we allow basically anything.

399
00:44:59.330 --> 00:45:10.669
Justin Florentine (Besu): But we prescribe specific forms of symmetric encryption, and then add to it later on as we need to.

400
00:45:11.230 --> 00:45:13.290
Gottfried Herold: What do you mean by symmetric encryption?

401
00:45:13.610 --> 00:45:21.909
Justin Florentine (Besu): Sorry, not symmetric, the, the actual decryption mechanism, the cha-cha poly stuff, I think that was what we were referring to.

402
00:45:21.910 --> 00:45:26.859
Gottfried Herold: Oh, yeah, the touch-up poly stuff, yeah, but the… oh, yeah, okay, so you want the…

403
00:45:27.430 --> 00:45:32.919
Gottfried Herold: But the cha-Chauly stuff is kind of… not the… is not the problematic part, to start with.

404
00:45:34.150 --> 00:45:42.429
Justin Florentine (Besu): Well, right, but I thought we were saying that we want to be a little bit more opinionated about, like, which…

405
00:45:42.580 --> 00:45:44.740
Justin Florentine (Besu): Algorithms that we allow for that.

406
00:45:46.030 --> 00:45:49.870
Gottfried Herold: I mean, currently, we only allow cha-cha, some cha-cha poly.

407
00:45:52.010 --> 00:45:52.530
Justin Florentine (Besu): Yes.

408
00:45:52.530 --> 00:46:11.369
Gottfried Herold: I mean, okay, so a bit of a clarity. I mean, this Chacha poly algorithm has only… I mean, okay, so basically what you have, you have these kind of key revealers, right? But what these key revealers basically do is, or how you should think about it from a cryptographic point of view, is they actually reveal not the key bit, they reveal the full message.

409
00:46:12.350 --> 00:46:16.150
Gottfried Herold: So there is no encryption going on in Lucid whatsoever.

410
00:46:16.150 --> 00:46:18.809
Justin Florentine (Besu): You could use this as just a commit reveal scheme, yeah.

411
00:46:18.810 --> 00:46:42.239
Gottfried Herold: Exactly, you can use this as a committed review scheme, and this structure poly thing is basically an optimization, a network optimization, because it allows you to sort of, send your ciphertext committed under the symmetry key up front, and then later you only have to use the Lucid mechanism for the actual decryption key. But as far as cryptography, for the interesting part of Lucid is concerned, basically, this decryption key is your message.

412
00:46:42.810 --> 00:46:43.720
Justin Florentine (Besu): Yep.

413
00:46:44.870 --> 00:46:48.130
Gottfried Herold: And it shouldn't think… you shouldn't think about it as a key, in a way.

414
00:46:48.500 --> 00:47:02.639
Gottfried Herold: Yeah, and the agnosticism basically is just… the interesting part of the agnosticism is just… which mechanism do we have that ensures that this key or this message actually gets eventually released?

415
00:47:02.830 --> 00:47:11.789
Gottfried Herold: And the fact that it's a cha-cha, whatever key, well, is not really, relevant for the agnosticism.

416
00:47:13.300 --> 00:47:15.910
Justin Florentine (Besu): So how is it different than the optionality issue?

417
00:47:17.690 --> 00:47:20.490
Gottfried Herold: I think what you mean by the optionality issue?

418
00:47:22.680 --> 00:47:33.689
Justin Florentine (Besu): So, let me just… maybe I'm not… maybe I'm misremembering the talking point here. Over-agnosticism of the Lucid design. Can we keep it, but constrain it? So, the problem… the problem with…

419
00:47:34.620 --> 00:47:38.700
Justin Florentine (Besu): This being overly agnostic, was…

420
00:47:38.700 --> 00:47:39.310
Gottfried Herold: the…

421
00:47:39.930 --> 00:47:59.809
Gottfried Herold: Yeah, the problem is, in some sense, that you, can sort of self-decrypt, or self-release, or self-reveal. The problem with the agnosticism is, and this is what leads to optionality in a way, is that we do not prescribe a mechanism that,

422
00:47:59.810 --> 00:48:06.640
Gottfried Herold: Make sure that the key gets revealed, or the message gets revealed, even if the original sender doesn't want it to.

423
00:48:09.320 --> 00:48:10.330
Justin Florentine (Besu): I see.

424
00:48:10.700 --> 00:48:11.230
Gottfried Herold: Nice.

425
00:48:11.550 --> 00:48:14.980
Gottfried Herold: It's completely orthogonal to the cha-cha pulley, whatever.

426
00:48:14.980 --> 00:48:24.090
Justin Florentine (Besu): Yes, I see what you're saying, right. And that's… that is the agnosticism, and that actually is… if we were less agnostic about it.

427
00:48:25.010 --> 00:48:28.430
Justin Florentine (Besu): We might have some mechanisms for reducing that optionality.

428
00:48:28.430 --> 00:48:46.839
Gottfried Herold: Exactly, because you could sort of prescribe… you could basically prescribe that, yeah, you have to actually rather… you have to actually encrypt it towards some, I don't know, towards some, trusted execution environment, or to some threshold encryption committee, or whatever, that will, as long…

429
00:48:47.100 --> 00:48:50.689
Gottfried Herold: That will eventually decrypt, whether you want it or not.

430
00:48:50.690 --> 00:48:51.500
Justin Florentine (Besu): Got it.

431
00:48:53.590 --> 00:48:58.659
Justin Florentine (Besu): Okay, so that's a design theme that we should further entertain, I think.

432
00:48:58.890 --> 00:49:22.260
Gottfried Herold: I mean… I mean, in a way, the point about Lucid was always that we do not have such a scheme, and so we do without, or we can do the best we can do without. The question that, sort of, I was raising in the criticism was just that, hey, and this is kind of the problem, and I really don't see much of a way around it, is can you take Lucid as is, maybe implement it, and get it on-chain, and then later change it

433
00:49:22.260 --> 00:49:29.399
Gottfried Herold: If we eventually, have some kind of cryptography that would allow us to do without this optionality, and.

434
00:49:29.400 --> 00:49:30.000
Justin Florentine (Besu): Yeah.

435
00:49:30.000 --> 00:49:30.750
Gottfried Herold: Yeah.

436
00:49:31.010 --> 00:49:36.479
Gottfried Herold: Sort of, is it upgradable to a future where we may have a good enough threshold encryption?

437
00:49:36.480 --> 00:49:41.979
Justin Florentine (Besu): That's a great segue to the thing I wanted to talk about, which is because… and I think you're right here, I think, like.

438
00:49:42.300 --> 00:49:44.950
Justin Florentine (Besu): If threshold encryption gets good enough.

439
00:49:44.950 --> 00:49:45.430
Gottfried Herold: Yes.

440
00:49:45.430 --> 00:49:47.540
Justin Florentine (Besu): Then this is broken.

441
00:49:48.450 --> 00:49:49.449
Gottfried Herold: What do you mean, broken?

442
00:49:49.450 --> 00:49:53.800
Justin Florentine (Besu): Well, the, the, kind of, kind of… I shouldn't say broken.

443
00:49:54.800 --> 00:49:55.429
Justin Florentine (Besu): I think…

444
00:49:55.430 --> 00:49:56.810
Gottfried Herold: It's superfluous.

445
00:49:56.810 --> 00:49:57.770
Justin Florentine (Besu): Yes, yes.

446
00:49:57.770 --> 00:50:00.060
Gottfried Herold: Supersede. It was superseded, in a way.

447
00:50:00.060 --> 00:50:01.179
Justin Florentine (Besu): Yes, it would be a complete…

448
00:50:01.180 --> 00:50:01.670
Gottfried Herold: better.

449
00:50:01.670 --> 00:50:06.110
Justin Florentine (Besu): You could not plug it into… you could not plug it into Lucid, you would build a whole new design.

450
00:50:06.700 --> 00:50:08.050
Gottfried Herold: Unfortunately.

451
00:50:08.050 --> 00:50:08.740
Justin Florentine (Besu): Yeah.

452
00:50:10.880 --> 00:50:15.670
Gottfried Herold: And I see very little way around this.

453
00:50:15.770 --> 00:50:34.200
Gottfried Herold: One reason being that, depending on details of the threshold, I mean, there is various flavors of threshold encryption, with slightly different functionality, and depending on which one you use, you would use a different scheme, and we wouldn't… we cannot know at the moment if

454
00:50:34.220 --> 00:50:36.810
Gottfried Herold: If we ever get one, which flavor it would be.

455
00:50:37.450 --> 00:50:41.769
Gottfried Herold: And the… The, sort of, the maple design would basically have to account for that.

456
00:50:42.900 --> 00:50:57.189
Justin Florentine (Besu): Okay, so we're guarding up on time here. The last bullet point that we had on here, let's just skip it, because I don't think we did any of this exploration. Did anybody explore using frame transactions and account abstraction for anonymous paymasters?

457
00:50:58.110 --> 00:50:59.799
Justin Florentine (Besu): I did not. I did not get to this.

458
00:50:59.800 --> 00:51:12.099
Gottfried Herold: I know, I didn't know. I mean, I just… I brought it up, essentially, but in the blog post, but, yeah. I mean, I have no idea about it, just wanted to make people aware of that. This would be something that we would need, essentially.

459
00:51:12.100 --> 00:51:16.189
Justin Florentine (Besu): Same here. So that'll get kicked down the road. Now…

460
00:51:16.360 --> 00:51:22.360
Justin Florentine (Besu): Threshold encryption. We keep talking about how Lucid exists because threshold encryption isn't ready yet.

461
00:51:22.480 --> 00:51:32.030
Justin Florentine (Besu): I am not a cryptographer, and is that a true statement, and is that a thing that I should be more open-minded about?

462
00:51:32.600 --> 00:51:34.919
Gottfried Herold: I mean, it is essentially a true statement.

463
00:51:35.760 --> 00:51:43.500
Andrei Lapets: I mean, it depends on who… it depends on who you ask, right? I mean, there's obviously threshold encryption is being used in production for, you know.

464
00:51:43.850 --> 00:52:02.000
Andrei Lapets: tens of millions and hundreds of millions of dollars right now by, you know, I mean, defense, other wallet providers. I don't think that there… I think you can make the argument for other applications like this, there's no production deployment of threshold encryption, so that's the argument you would have to make if you want to make that argument.

465
00:52:02.700 --> 00:52:16.689
Gottfried Herold: I mean, to be fair, also, you have to be aware that we have very unique, or very… we have, kind of, design constraints that other applications do not have, and there is a bit more… a bit more clear statement would be we have nothing that is good enough for our purpose.

466
00:52:16.730 --> 00:52:35.609
Gottfried Herold: Which, includes, in particular, the problem that you want something that is post-quantum secure. This is a big, big, big issue, because almost all threshold encryption solutions that are… that exist right now in the literature are basically based on pair… pairings, which are not post-quantum secure, so any kind of… they are basically not future-safe.

467
00:52:35.660 --> 00:52:59.589
Gottfried Herold: And among those, that are not, you have the other problem that there is usually a very high setup cost involved, oftentimes, or large keys, or much communication that scales with the committee size, or with… that is with the size of the people who sort of need to decrypt, or how often the decryption committee changes, and whatnot. So, if you have a kind of a small number of participants to it.

468
00:52:59.890 --> 00:53:19.480
Gottfried Herold: it would… it might even work, and that's the other question, is do you sort of decrypt every transaction individually? Do you decrypt them in bulk? There is a lot of things you can do. I mean, Benedict actually wrote some notes about, sort of, the requirement list. It's long, and we basically have nothing that fits our requirements. Other applications do have

469
00:53:19.490 --> 00:53:25.400
Gottfried Herold: Other requirements, and the existing schemes might fit for them.

470
00:53:25.590 --> 00:53:27.839
Gottfried Herold: But we do not, unfortunately.

471
00:53:28.770 --> 00:53:29.700
Justin Florentine (Besu): Okay.

472
00:53:30.990 --> 00:53:33.230
Justin Florentine (Besu): Can I just keep asking that every week?

473
00:53:35.580 --> 00:53:37.959
Justin Florentine (Besu): Is it ready yet? Is it ready yet? Is it ready yet?

